      <bioghist id="aspace_a6fc083cc2d850a82d7548ff47fbd256">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>In 1915 Charles-Edward Amory Winslow founded the Department of Public Health at the Yale Medical School. Amory's definition of public health was "the science and the art of preventing disease, prolonging life and promoting physical health and efficiency through organized community efforts for the sanitation of the environment, the control of community infections, the education of the individual in principles and personal hygiene, the organization of medical and nursing services for the early diagnosis and preventive treatment of disease, and the development of the social machinery which will ensure to every individual a standard of living adequate for the maintenance of health; organizing these benefits in such a fashion as to enable every citizen to realize his birthright of health and longevity." The Department curriculum included public health principles, public health administration and vital statistics augmented by courses in the Yale College Departments of Bacteriology, Immunology, Medicine, Pathology, Pediatrics, Physiological Chemistry, Sanitary Engineering, and Zoology. In the 1920s the Yale Medical School Department of Public Health helped launch major health reform in Connecticut including improvement of health laws and creation of the State Department of Public Health.</p>
         <p>sources: https://ysph.yale.edu/about-school-of-public-health/history/
https://web.archive.org/web/20090723231430/http://www.med.yale.edu/library/exhibits/publichealth/</p>
      </bioghist>
      <bioghist id="aspace_3798cda83315265389208593426dcb38">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Charles-Edward Amory Winslow (1877-1957) was a leader in the field of public health and public health education in the United States. He was Born in Boston, received a B.S. degree from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1898 and an M.S. degree from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1899. He taught sanitary bacteriology at  the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and the University of Chicago; biology at the College of the City of New York; and public health and nursing at Columbia University Teachers College before being appointed as Anna M. R. Lauder Professor of Public Health in the Yale University Medical School, where he remained from 1915-1945. From 1914-1915 Winslow was director of the Division of Public Health Education, New York State Department of Health and from 1910-1922 was the curator of public health in the American Museum of Natural History. He was editor of the <title>
               <part>Journal of Bacteriology</part>
            </title> from 1916-1944, of <title>
               <part>The Nation's Health</part>
            </title> from 1922-1925, and of the <title>
               <part>American Journal of Public Health</part>
            </title> from 1944-1954.  Winslow was also a member of numerous national and international organizations related to public health.</p>
      </bioghist>
